drafts.interfaceChange:
Flip the three seam declarations that are structurally identical — packages/db/src/sql.ts, packages/migrate/src/types.ts, and KernelDatabase in packages/kernel/src/kernel.ts — from value-returning to Promise-returning:

  interface SqlStatement {
    run(params?: unknown[]): Promise<{ changes: number; lastInsertRowid: number | bigint }>;
    get(params?: unknown[]): Promise<unknown>;
    all(params?: unknown[]): Promise<unknown[]>;
  }
  interface SqlDatabase {
    exec(sql: string): Promise<unknown>;     // was unknown
    prepare(sql: string): SqlStatement;       // prepare STAYS sync — it only builds a statement object; binding+execution is what awaits
  }

Note prepare() does NOT become async: keeping it sync means the call sites stay `db.prepare(sql).get(params)` → just add one `await` at the front, no restructuring. In @keel/db/src/queries.ts the four terminals become async and await the driver: get() → `const row = await sql.prepare(stmt).get(params)`; all() → `const rows = await sql.prepare(stmt).all(params); return rows.map(hydrate)`; count() → `const row = (await sql.prepare(stmt).get(params)) as CountRow`; run() (insert/update/delete) → `const { changes } = await sql.prepare(stmt).run(params)`; insert .returning().get() → await; and Db.exec becomes `exec: async (statement) => { await sql.exec(statement); }`. The public Db terminal signatures become: get(): Promise<InferRow<T> | undefined>; all(): Promise<InferRow<T>[]>; count(): Promise<number>; run(): Promise<{ changes: number }>; InsertReturning.get(): Promise<InferRow<T>>; Db.exec(sql): Promise<void>. The chain MODIFIERS (where/orderBy/limit/offset, .values, .set, .returning) stay synchronous and return the same builder objects — only the terminal verbs await. createDb's signature is unchanged structurally (still createDb(sql: SqlDatabase): Db); its return type's terminals are now async. openSqlite's `OpenSqlite { db: KernelDatabase; close }` is unchanged in shape; only db's method return types become Promises.

drafts.sqliteDriverPlan:
openSqlite (packages/runtime/src/sqlite.ts) is the single adapter and the dev default; the underlying engines (better-sqlite3, bun:sqlite) stay synchronous — we do NOT swap drivers. The adapter simply presents the sync results behind the async interface:

  const db: KernelDatabase = {
    exec: async (sql) => raw.exec(sql),
    prepare: (sql) => {
      const statement = raw.prepare(sql);
      return {
        run: async (params = []) => statement.run(...params),
        get: async (params = []) => statement.get(...params),
        all: async (params = []) => statement.all(...params),
      };
    },
  };

`async` wrapping a sync return yields a resolved Promise — zero behavior change, zero added latency on the dev path, zero-config local preserved. The SqliteHandle interface (raw engine shape) stays sync — better-sqlite3 and bun:sqlite are untouched. The SqliteEngines injection seam already lets tests substitute fake engines; the fake engines stay sync and the wrapper makes them async, so the fallback branch (better → bun) is still covered under Node/vitest without ever loading bun:sqlite. IMPORTANT param-shape caveat: this spread adapter (`...params`) only works for POSITIONAL array params. @keel/queue currently passes NAMED objects (`@queue`, `@name`) straight through a DIFFERENT db wiring (it takes a raw SqlDatabase, not openSqlite's). Queue must either keep its own named-param-capable handle or be migrated to positional `?` (see hazards/ripple) — openSqlite's positional adapter cannot bind named objects via spread.

drafts.interfaceChange:
The seam is packages/db/src/sql.ts (mirrored verbatim in packages/kernel/src/kernel.ts KernelDatabase, packages/migrate/src/types.ts, packages/cache/src/types.ts, packages/queue/src/types.ts). All four become Promise-returning, positional-array-only:

  export interface SqlStatement {
    run(params?: unknown[]): Promise<{ changes: number; lastInsertRowid: number | bigint }>;
    get(params?: unknown[]): Promise<unknown>;
    all(params?: unknown[]): Promise<unknown[]>;
  }
  export interface SqlDatabase {
    exec(sql: string): Promise<void>;          // was `unknown`; settle to void since no caller reads it
    prepare(sql: string): SqlStatement;        // STAYS SYNC — returns a statement handle, not a query result
    transaction<T>(fn: (tx: SqlDatabase) => Promise<T>): Promise<T>;  // NEW, first-class
  }

Key decisions:
- prepare() stays synchronous and returns a statement object; only the terminals run/get/all touch the wire and return Promises. This preserves the existing prepare-once-reuse pattern (cache/src/sql-store.ts caches `selectByKey`/`upsert`/`deleteByKey`/`deleteAll` at construction; content-store/persist.ts caches `statement`) without forcing those modules to await at construction. The pg adapter makes prepare() lazy (see pgAdapterPlan).
- run() keeps lastInsertRowid in the type for SQLite + queue's `Number(result.lastInsertRowid)` (queue.ts:200); the pg adapter populates it from RETURNING id (see pgAdapterPlan).
- transaction() is added to the seam now (not deferred to Phase 2) because the migrator already needs BEGIN/COMMIT/ROLLBACK and doing it via raw exec("BEGIN") races on a pool. This is the clean cut: one correct primitive instead of string DDL.
- @keel/db terminals in packages/db/src/queries.ts become async: SelectQuery.get/all/count → Promise (lines 94-104, 162-199), InsertValues.run + InsertReturning.get (lines 226-232, 275-290), UpdateSet.run (line 303, 337-344), DeleteBuilder...run (362, 371-374), and Db.exec (line 394, 409-411). hydrate()/bind()/renderSelect()/compileInsert() stay pure/sync — only the `sql.prepare(stmt).get(params)` calls gain `await`. createDb() itself stays sync (it wires closures).

createDb terminals — concretely, e.g. queries.ts get() becomes:
  async get(): Promise<InferRow<T> | undefined> {
    const { sql: stmt, params } = renderSelect(...);
    const row = await sql.prepare(stmt).get(params);
    return row == null ? undefined : hydrate(state.table, row);
  }
and count(): `const row = (await sql.prepare(stmt).get(params)) as CountRow; return Number(row.c);`

drafts.sqliteDriverPlan:
The two SQLite engines (better-sqlite3 under Node, bun:sqlite under Bun) are synchronous; they present the async interface by trivially wrapping each terminal in an already-resolved Promise. The adaptation lives where it already lives: packages/runtime/src/sqlite.ts openSqlite() (lines 66-87). SqliteHandle (lines 31-41) is unchanged — the raw engine stays sync; only the KernelDatabase wrapper changes:

  const db: SqlDatabase = {
    exec: async (sql) => { raw.exec(sql); },
    prepare: (sql) => {
      const statement = raw.prepare(sql);              // sync, once
      return {
        run: async (params = []) => statement.run(...params),
        get: async (params = []) => statement.get(...params),
        all: async (params = []) => statement.all(...params),
      };
    },
    transaction: async (fn) => {
      raw.exec("BEGIN");
      try { const out = await fn(db); raw.exec("COMMIT"); return out; }
      catch (e) { try { raw.exec("ROLLBACK"); } catch {} throw e; }
    },
  };

Notes:
- async fn whose body is sync is the canonical zero-cost wrap; an `async` function that returns a value yields a resolved Promise — no microtask hazard for correctness. This is exactly ADR 0006 step 1.3 ("trivially async").
- The transaction() here runs on the single in-process SQLite connection (no pool), so BEGIN/COMMIT is safe serially. Because the SQLite handle is one connection, nested/concurrent transactions are NOT supported on SQLite (documented limitation); the migrator runs migrations serially so this is fine.
- sqlite-drivers.ts (the untestable native require / bun dynamic import, excluded from coverage) is UNCHANGED — the engines stay sync; only the covered sqlite.ts wrapper gains `async`. The fake-engine tests in runtime/test/sqlite.test.ts keep working with the same sync fakes, now asserted through `await`.
- bun:sqlite path still never executes under the Node gate; the wrapper logic that DOES is fully covered via fakes (per the file's own coverage doctrine, sqlite.ts lines 19-23).
